Diagram Explanation
The browser receives the URL entered by the user.
A DNS lookup translates www.google.com into an IP address.
A TCP connection is established to the server IP using port 443 for HTTPS.
A TLS/SSL handshake creates an encrypted communication channel.
The request passes through a firewall, where security rules are applied.
A load balancer distributes the request to an available backend server.
The web server receives the request and forwards dynamic requests to the application server.
The application server executes business logic and requests data from the database.
The database returns the requested data.
The application server generates the HTML response.
The web server sends the encrypted HTTPS response back to the browser.
The browser renders the page and displays the Google homepage.
